The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Bank of Baroda will merge its housing arm, BOB Housing Finance Ltd, with itself subject to approvals. The scheme of merger was approved by the BoB board at a meeting held recently, the bank has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. In March this year, the bank had bought back the National Housing Bank?s 32.89 per cent stake in BOB Housing Finance to make it a wholly-owned subsidiary. 

 Pearl Global Ltd?s net profit was Rs 6.43 crore in 2005-06 against Rs 3.41 crore in 2004-05. Net revenue rose 31.9 per cent to Rs 159.5 crore from Rs 120.9 crore in the previous fiscal. The company?s operating profit was Rs 17.1 crore compared with Rs 7.5 crore in the previous year. The board has declared a 30 per cent dividend for 2005-06, subject to shareholders? approval. 

 The Apparel Export Promotion Council (AEPC) is putting in place strategies to step up exports. The council plans to conduct research on global trends and participate in international trade fairs and exhibitions to promote collaborations with foreign companies.

 The ministry of commerce has cleared the proposal of DS Constructions to set up two multi-product special economic zones (SEZs) in Haryana and Himachal Pradesh. The SEZs will be set up at an estimated investment of Rs 10,000 crore in Haryana and Rs 2,000 crore in Himachal Pradesh. 

 Aptech Ltd has been rated by TrainingOutsourcing.com as one of the 20 global training outsourcing service provider (OSP) companies. The list has adapted criteria such as scope and depth of services provided, geographic reach, revenues, and client engagements. 

 Radha Madhav Corporation has posted a net profit of Rs 3.02 crore for the year ended March 31, 2006. The company?s total income was Rs 44.78 crore during the year. Its earnings per share (EPS) stood at Rs 3.27. 

 Yahoo! India has unveiled a preview of its redesigned flagship destination, yahoo.co.in homepage. The new homepage will provide quicker services and latest news to users. 

 Shree Cement has despatched 3.9 lakh tonnes of cement in June 2006 against 2.5 lakh tonnes in June 2005, recording a 54 per cent growth. 

 LG Electronics is conducting training programmes to enhance its customer service network. The company has set up four training centres in Greater Noida, Pune, Chennai and Calcutta. 

